                                        2193,
                                        3108
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": "We argue that, to better engage users in multi- session conversations (MSCs), a chatbot should maintain a long- term memory of historical contexts, which allows the chatbot to reengage the user appropriately when similar contexts reemerge. By learning from historical conversations, the chatbot should gradually refine its understanding of and deepen its relationship with the user. Figure 1 shows an example of a two- session conversation between a user and a chatbot. In the second session, the chatbot infers that Sonny is a cat and generates the response based on the history information that Sonny likes watching TV with the user."
                                }
                            ]
